  "prompt": "Is there a Church that doesn't believe in Trinity?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several Christian denominations that do not believe in the doctrine of the Trinity, which defines God as one Being in three persons: the Father, the Son (Jesus Christ), and the Holy Spirit. Some of the groups that reject the Trinity include:\n\n1. **Unitarians**: Unitarianism emphasizes the oneness of God and typically denies the divinity of Jesus in the same sense that Trinitarians believe. They see Jesus as a moral teacher and prophet but not as God incarnate.\n\n2. **Jehovah's Witnesses**: They believe that Jesus is the Son of God but not part of a Trinity. They view the Holy Spirit as God's active force rather than a distinct person.\n\n3. **Christadelphians**: This group believes that Jesus is the Son of God but denies the pre-existence and eternal nature of Christ, viewing Him instead as a created being.\n\n4. **Oneness Pentecostals**: They reject the traditional doctrine of the Trinity and instead adhere to a modalistic understanding of God, believing that God is one who has revealed Himself in different modes or aspects, including as the Father, Son, and Holy Spirit.\n\nThese groups interpret the Bible and the nature of God differently than mainstream Trinitarian denominations, which include Roman Catholics, Orthodox Christians, and most Protestant groups.",
